<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 20.1pt 5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Family Rights Group (LAI 0017)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 20.1pt 6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 20.1pt 5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What is Family Rights Group</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 20.1pt 5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Family Rights Group is the charity in England and Wales that advises families whose children are involved with, or require, local authority services because of welfare needs or concerns. We promote policies and practices that help children to be raised safely and thrive within their family and community and give families a voice when decisions are made about their children’s lives.  We campaign for effective support to help struggling parents and family and friends carers who are raising children that cannot live at home.  We provide a free, confidential telephone and email advice service assisting over 7000 callers per year. Typically, this involves advising:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 20.1pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">parents of their legal position, helping them to understand the child protection concerns and supporting them to work with the local authority to make, and implement, safe plans for their child; and </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 20.1pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">relatives and friends about taking on the care of a child who is unable to live with their parents, and the implications of different legal options.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 20.1pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 20.1pt 5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> lead th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e Kinship Care Alliance, which comprises a number of voluntary organisations working with family and friends carers, local authorities and academics. The Alliance develops and promotes a joint policy agenda aimed at preventing children from being unnecessarily raised outside their family and securing improved support to enhance outcomes for children who are raised in family and friends care.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 20.1pt 5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Our concerns </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have grave concerns about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the following government proposals to reform legal aid which affect our client group:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o introduce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a residence test for all civil legal aid cases, limiting legal aid to those with a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘strong connection’ with the UK</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To only pay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> providers of legal services for work done if permission is granted.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To end legal aid for borderline cases.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Residence Test</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We support the revision to the proposed residence test (in the ‘Next Steps’ document) so that children under 12 months won’t need to meet the requirement of at least 12 months of previous, lawful residence.  However we are concerned that paragraph 1.24 of ‘Next Steps’ then says that the government has now also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“revised the proposed residence test…. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">to include exceptions for certain types of cases, where we accept that there should be no requirement for an individual to demonstrate a strong connection to the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We hope this means that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">residence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">test won’t apply to parties to proceedings under Part IV of the Children Act 1989 and the Adoption and Children Act 2002</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (as suggested in the Impact Assessment document)</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but since we have not seen this spelt out we include our concerns below should that not be the case: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The current position is that all parents and others with parental responsibility are entitled to non means and non merits tested legal aid for care and emergency protection order appl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ications</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Legal aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in placement order and adoption proceedings is means and merits tested.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The effect is that parents (and others with parental responsibility) almost always have legal aid, hence they are represented when decisions are made by a court which may result in their children being removed from their care permanently against their wishes. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are particularly concerned that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">residence pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oposal may result in parents whose children are subject to such proceedings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NOT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">getting legal aid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unless</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> they have lived </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lawfully</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the country for 12 months</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and are lawfully resident at the time of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">applicationUNLESS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a clear exception to this rule is made for them. If such an exception were not made, the proposal would seriously undermine their fair treatment in the decision-making process when the State decides that their child sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be removed from their care against their wishes. This would not only have a potentially detrimental effect on the individual lives of the children and parents involved, but also would be very likely to constitute a breach of both their human rights under Articles 6 and 8 of the ECHR, imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lemented</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in domestic law by the Human Rights Act 1998.</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  It is established by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">European Court of Justice that Article 6 rights to a fair trial require legal aid for children and family members in care proceedings etc.</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Without </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> express exception</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">individual parents (and others with parental responsibility) would have to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pass the residence test </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to get legal aid. For those who could not, they would have to apply to the Legal Aid Agency under exceptional criteria in LASPO</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, for legal aid to prevent a breach of their human rights. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e have no doubt that in some cases it would lead directly to children being unnecessarily separated from their families and/or forcibly adopted without the parents having legal representation.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Concerns about families’ access to judicial review: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We advise many parents/family members in situations where redress or review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of decisions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is not available through family proceedings but only through judicial review. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This arises particularly when local authorities make administrative decisions about the care and support of children outside of any legal process. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Eg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: </span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.03pt; padding-left:18.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If a local authority wrongly declines to pay mandatory foster care allowance or pays this (or other discretionary payments) at an unlawful rate</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.03pt; padding-left:18.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Or if a child is living at home with a parent or grandparent under a Care Order and a local authority plans to remove them without consultation or notice of what they were worried about or where some lesser measure would do</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[vi]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.03pt; padding-left:18.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Or when children drift with care plans unimplemented like ‘statutory orphans’ ‘freed for adoption’ though no adoptive placement has been found.</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is already incredibly difficult for the family members we advise to access judicial review due to the complexity of the law, risk of costs against them and means testing for legal aid. Their legitimate access to judicial review proceedings will be further compounded by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the proposals to:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nly pay their legal services providers for work done, if leave is then granted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This will make it even harder for our clients to find providers willing to take on their cases particularly if the matter is urgent, complex or justifiably pushing at the boundaries of established law.</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Remove legal aid in borderline case. This involves amending the merits criteria to remove civil legal aid for cases that are assessed as having ‘borderline’ prospects of success. Such cases are already only funded where they have ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a significant wider public interest’ or are ‘of overwhelming importance to the individual’ so the measure is likely to prevent some important but challenging cases.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Yet, unlike family proceedings it is effectively impossible to happy for judicial review as a litigant in person.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">25 September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Para 15 at page 6 of Impact Assessment MOJ194 published with Next Steps: 5 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Re BS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">B-S (Children) Court of Appeal [2013] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> 1146</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn3"></a><a href="#_ednref3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> P, C and S v United Kingdom (App.No.56547/00) (2002) 35 EHRR 31  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn4"></a><a href="#_ednref4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> S.10 LASPOA 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn5"></a><a href="#_ednref5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> R (SA) v Kent County Council [2011] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> 1303</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_edn6"></a><a href="#_ednref6">[vi]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">Re M (Care: Challenging Local Authority Decisions)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal"> [2001] 2FLR </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">1300; </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">Re L (Care</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">Assessment: Fair Trial) Proceedings: Disclosure of Local Authority Decision-Making Process)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal"> [2002] 2 FLR 730; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">Re: G (Care: Challenge to local Authority’s decisions)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">[2003] EWHC 551 (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">Fam</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">), Family Law June 2003, 389.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><a name="_edn7"></a><a href="#_ednref7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">A and S (Children) v Lancashire CC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">  [2012] EWHC 1689 (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Fam</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">) 21 June 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>